               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18380820-name-1472" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18380820-name-1472" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18380820-name-1472" type="surname" value="CARD"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18380820-name-1472" type="given" value="JAMES"></interp>JAMES CARD</persName>
                  </hi>. I am footman to Sir James Clark. I placed a cloak of his on the front seat of the carriage, on the 21st of August, at a quarter past three o'clock—it was an open carriage—this is his cloak—(<hi rend="italic">looking at it</hi>.)</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18380820-name-1473" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18380820-name-1473" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18380820-name-1473" type="surname" value="TOWN"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18380820-name-1473" type="given" value="THOMAS"></interp>THOMAS TOWN</persName>
                  </hi>. I am coachman to the prosecutor. I was driving the carriage, and saw three <hi rend="italic">chaps</hi> about Hanover-square—the prisoner was one—they came down the pavement and turned back, but after that passed the carriage, and took the cloak off the front seat—I called to them—they all ran off, turned into Maddox-street, and I lost sight of them.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Prisoner. Q.</hi> How do you know I was one of the three? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Because I had noticed him more than any of the rest, in consequence of an impudent answer he made to some workmen.</p>
